<article>
    <h1>Know your skin&#xAD;care ABCs</h1>
    <h2>Amanda Chai breaks down the five trend&#xAD;ing in&#xAD;gre&#xAD;di&#xAD;ents to keep a look&#xAD;out for</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201023/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-23"><time>2020-10-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | STYLE</span>
        - <span role="byline">aman&#xAD;dac@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>How well do you know your vi­ta­mins A, B, and C in skin­care?</p>
    <p>While tak­ing in­ter­est in one’s skin­care has been a trend in the past few years, 2020 may just be the year the ev­ery­day con­sumer took skin­care ed­u­ca­tion into her own hands.</p>
    <p>No longer are in­gre­di­ents the do­main of just der­ma­tol­o­gists. Ac­cord­ing to data an­a­lyt­ics firm Glob­alData’s Con­sumer Sur­vey Q3 2019, 78 per cent of re­spon­dents agreed that they pay a “medium/high/very high” amount of at­ten­tion to the in­gre­di­ents used in their beauty and groom­ing prod­ucts.</p>
    <p>This year, with more time at home and a new, pan­demic-in­duced em­pha­sis on skin­care over makeup, con­sumers are tak­ing a more ac­tive ap­proach to un­der­stand­ing the sci­ence be­hind the prod­ucts.</p>
    <p>Many of these in­gre­di­ents are by no means new. But as con­sumers de­mand more trans­parency in their prod­uct for­mu­la­tions, brands ap­pear to be more forth­com­ing about the use of cer­tain in­gre­di­ents in their prod­ucts.</p>
    <p>Here are five trend­ing in­gre­di­ents to keep a look­out for the next time you go skin­care shop­ping.</p>

